<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Entitlements for the Developer ID (notarized) build.

  Notarization requires the hardened runtime, which denies a set of capabilities
  unless the app explicitly asks for them. This file is that request, and it is
  deliberately minimal — every entitlement here is one the app provably needs,
  because each one is a hole in the runtime's protections.

  Only the microphone needs an entitlement:

    · Microphone — the voice path records through MediaRecorder inside WKWebView
      (frontend/src/lib/useVoiceRecorder.ts). Under the hardened runtime an
      Info.plist usage string is NOT sufficient; without the entitlement the
      recorder fails at runtime while the rest of the app looks fine.

  Deliberately NOT here:

    · Screen capture (internal/capture, kbinani/screenshot) and the global voice
      hotkey (internal/hotkey, robotn/gohook) are gated by TCC — Screen Recording
      and Input Monitoring — which the user grants in System Settings. They are
      permissions, not entitlements, so nothing belongs here for them.

    · Network access. That is restricted by the App Sandbox, which this app does
      not use; the hardened runtime alone does not block outbound connections.

    · com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit. WKWebView runs JavaScript in Apple's own
      out-of-process WebContent service, which carries its own entitlements — the
      host app does not need JIT rights of its own.

  If a capability breaks only in the signed build, this file is the first place
  to look, but add to it only with evidence — not pre-emptively.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>com.apple.security.device.audio-input</key>
	<true/>
</dict>
</plist>
